Url.Title: Getting started with Sumo Logic
Url.Abstract: Getting started with Sumo Logic The Sumo Logic solution provides everything you need to conduct real-time forensics and log management for all of your IT data—without having to perform complex installations or upgrades, and without the need to manage and scale any hardware or storage. With fully elastic scalability, Sumo Logic is a fit for any size deployment.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic Overview
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic Overview The Sumo Logic solution provides everything you need to conduct real-time forensics and log management for all of your IT data—without having to perform complex installations or upgrades, and without the need to manage and scale any hardware or storage. With fully elastic scalability, Sumo Logic is a fit for any size deployment.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic components
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic components A Sumo Logic solution is comprised of just a few components: Sumo Logic Collectors and Sources, the Sumo Logic Cloud, and the Sumo Logic Web Application. A Collector is a small application that gathers log data from your servers and sends it to the Sumo Logic Cloud. Using the Sumo Logic Web Application, you can interact with and analyze your data in the cloud in real time.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic Source Types
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic Source Types There are several different types of Sources that can be configured for Installed and Hosted Collectors.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic accounts
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic accounts There are two types of Sumo Logic accounts: Enterprise and Free. Sumo Logic Enterprise

Url.Title: Designing your deployment
Url.Abstract: Designing your deployment Sumo Logic Installed Collectors are lightweight and efficient. You can choose to install a small number of Collectors to minimize maintenance or just because you want to keep your topology simple. Alternatively, you can choose to install many Collectors on many machines to distribute the bandwidth impact across your network rather than having it centralized. In addition, you'll want to consider Sumo Logic Hosted Collectors, which reside in the Cloud, allowing for seamless collection from Amazon S3 buckets and HTTP Sources.

Url.Title: Setting up Installed Collectors and configuring Sources
Url.Abstract: Setting up Installed Collectors and configuring Sources The Sumo Logic solution provides everything you need to conduct real-time forensics and log management for all of your IT data—without having to perform complex installations or upgrades, and without the need to manage and scale any hardware or storage. With fully elastic scalability, Sumo Logic is a fit for any size deployment.

Url.Title: Installed Collector Requirements
Url.Abstract: Installed Collector Requirements Sumo Logic Local Collectors are lightweight applications with few hardware requirements. To ensure your system can connect to the Sumo Logic service, you can check system requirements and do a quick connectivity test.

Url.Title: What's the difference between Collector types?
Url.Abstract: What's the difference between Collector types? Installed Collectors and Hosted Collectors are used in much different ways:

Url.Title: Where should I set up Installed Collectors?
Url.Abstract: Where should I set up Installed Collectors? When you are deciding where to install Collectors, you have a large number of options to choose from. When you are thinking about your log collections, consider your network topology, your available bandwidth, and your domains or user groups.

Url.Title: Installed Collector volume guidelines and hardware specs
Url.Abstract: Installed Collector volume guidelines and hardware specs When considering the amount of data you'll be collecting with Sumo Logic it can be very helpful to understand the volume an Installed Collector can handle.

Url.Title: Testing connectivity
Url.Abstract: Testing connectivity To ensure you have the required access and connectivity to the Sumo Logic service, there are a couple of checks you can do from the machine where you want to install a Collector.

Url.Title: Setting up Installed Collectors and Sources
Url.Abstract: Setting up Installed Collectors and Sources Installed Collectors and Sources are configured on machines in your deployment. There are a few steps in this process:

Url.Title: Step 1. Download Installed Collector software
Url.Abstract: Step 1. Download Installed Collector software In the following steps we'll download the Collector from the Sumo Logic Web Application.

Url.Title: Downloading a Collector from a static URL
Url.Abstract: Downloading a Collector from a static URL Use the following URLs to download the most recent version of a Collector. The URLs are static; the version of the Collector will be updated each time there is a release or patch.

Url.Title: Step 2. Install a Collector
Url.Abstract: Step 2. Install a Collector Make sure to install the Collector on a server with network connectivity to the machines from which you want to gather files. You'll want to run the installer on your server with root or Administrator privileges.

Url.Title: Running a Collector on a User Account
Url.Abstract: Running a Collector on a User Account During installation, you can choose to run as the root or you can choose to run the Collector from a specific user account. This option can be very helpful in situations where you don't want offer Sumo Logic full access to the computer where the Collector is installed; instead the Collector assumes the limitations and privileges of the user account.

Url.Title: Configuring an Installed Collector behind a proxy
Url.Abstract: Configuring an Installed Collector behind a proxy If you need to connect to Sumo Logic via a proxy you'll need to edit the wrapper.conf file with the proxy IP, port, user name, and password properties. You can find the wrapper.conf file in the installation directory.

Url.Title: Step 3. Add a Source
Url.Abstract: Step 3. Add a Source After setting up an Installed Collector you'll add Sources. If you set up a Source when you installed your Collector, you can create an additional Source type.

Url.Title: Configuring a Local File Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring a Local File Source To collect log messages from the same machine where a Collector is installed, create a Local File Source. If you are editing a Source, metadata changes are reflected going forward. Metadata for previously collected logs will not be retroactively changed.

Url.Title: Configuring a Remote File Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring a Remote File Source Remote file tail data is collected via SSH. If you are collecting from a Windows machine, please see the note following on Prerequisite for Windows. If you are editing a Source, metadata changes are reflected going forward. Metadata for previously collected log data will not be retroactively changed.

Url.Title: Configuring a Local Windows Events Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring a Local Windows Events Source Set up a Local Windows Event Log Source to collect localevents you would normally see in the Windows Event Viewer. Setting up a Local Windows Event Source is a very quick process. There are no prerequisites for setting up the Source, and you'll begin collecting logs within a minute or so.

Url.Title: Configuring a Remote Windows Event Log Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring a Remote Windows Event Log Source Set up a Remote Windows Event Log Source to collect remote events you would normally see in the Windows Event Viewer. Before collecting Windows Events from a remote machine, you'll need to configure a few settings.

Url.Title: Prerequisites for Windows Collections
Url.Abstract: Prerequisites for Windows Collections Sumo Logic requires a few extra steps when you set up collections in a Windows environment:

Url.Title: Collecting Windows Logs from a UNC Share Path
Url.Abstract: Collecting Windows Logs from a UNC Share Path As an alternative to using SSH for remote Windows collections, Sumo Logic Collectors can collect files remotely using CIFS/SMB by configuring a Local File Source (not a Remote File Source) with a UNC share path.

Url.Title: Using a third-party client to handle SSH in Windows
Url.Abstract: Using a third-party client to handle SSH in Windows There are two options for collecting Windows logs remotely:

Url.Title: Configuring a Syslog Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring a Syslog Source A Sumo Logic Syslog Source operates like a syslog server listening on the designated port to receive syslog messages. Set your syslog-enabled devices to send syslog data to the same port you specify in Sumo Logic Syslog Source configuration.

Url.Title: Configuring a Script Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring a Script Source If you need to collect data that isn't stored in log files (like system performance metrics, database records, or perhaps data output from third-party monitoring solutions) you can use a Script Source that uses a script to fetch those custom sources of data. The script executes at defined intervals and then sends the data to Sumo Logic for analysis. A Script Source allows you to collect all sorts of data from any supported OS, including data from command-line tools (for example, as iostat) or transient or unstable data sources.

Url.Title: Troubleshooting Script Source Issues
Url.Abstract: Troubleshooting Script Source Issues To check the status of a Script Source you can look at the Collectors tab of the Sumo Logic Web Application. If you need more information about the reason a Script Source isn't generating log data, you can look at the Collector's logs to help identify what needs to change.

Url.Title: Advanced Topic: Using CRON Expressions
Url.Abstract: Advanced Topic: Using CRON Expressions If you're configuring a Script Source and need to specify a frequency that's different than any existing option, you can specify a CRON expression to collect data at a custom frequency.

Url.Title: Configuring a Script Action
Url.Abstract: Configuring a Script Action Unlike all other Source varieties, a Script Action receives data uploads triggered by a scheduled search. The script you create defines how data is consumed; for example, you could fire SNMP traps based on the result of the search.

Url.Title: Setting Source timestamp options
Url.Abstract: Setting Source timestamp options When configuring a Source you can choose to use the Sumo Logic default timestamp parsing settings, or you can specify a custom format for Sumo Logic to parse timestamps in your log messages. In addition, you can choose how the time zone in your log data is handled.

Url.Title: Supported Timestamp Conventions
Url.Abstract: Supported Timestamp Conventions As long as the following conventions are followed, Sumo Logic can parse timestamps from log messages:

Url.Title: Step 4. Complete the setup
Url.Abstract: Step 4. Complete the setup After completing the setup, the Collector starts automatically and runs as a service. The Collector also starts automatically after rebooting.

Url.Title: Recommendations for Collections
Url.Abstract: Recommendations for Collections To help get you started with collecting log files from various systems, Sumo Logic has compiled a list of recommended files to collect. See the list for your target server:

Url.Title: Recommendations for Linux Collections
Url.Abstract: Recommendations for Linux Collections Many Sumo customers make extensive use of the Linux operating system for running their applications and for general infrastructure services. The question has come up "What should I be collecting from these devices, and what should I be looking for?"

Url.Title: Recommendations for Apache Collections
Url.Abstract: Recommendations for Apache Collections This section describes how to configure your Apache logs to feed into the Sumo Logic Service so that they can be aggregated and analyzed.

Url.Title: Recommendations for Windows IIS Collections
Url.Abstract: Recommendations for Windows IIS Collections This section describes how to configure your Windows IIS logs to feed into the Sumo Logic Service so that they can be aggregated and analyzed.

Url.Title: Recommendations for Tomcat Collections
Url.Abstract: Recommendations for Tomcat Collections Apache Tomcat is an open source software implementation of the Java Servlet and JavaServer Pages technologies. It is the most common Servlet engine in use today. Many of our customers have developed their custom web applications using Apache Tomcat and would like to leverage the Sumo Logic service to collect, manage and analyze these logs.

Url.Title: Advanced Collector installation
Url.Abstract: Advanced Collector installation In addition to installing via the Web Application, there are several options for silent/scripted installation.

Url.Title: Installation using the Collector Management API
Url.Abstract: Installation using the Collector Management API The newest method that allows you to install Collectors and configure Sources across a deployment is our Collector Management API. The Collector Management API supports all of the configuration options found in the Source setup UI--including filters. In addition, you can flag a Collector as ephemeral or clobber the Collector via the API.

Url.Title: Unattended installation from a Linux script
Url.Abstract: Unattended installation from a Linux script There are three methods of silent (unattended) installation for Linux computers:

Url.Title: Unattended installation from a Linux script using the Collector Management API
Url.Abstract: Unattended installation from a Linux script using the Collector Management API There are three methods of silent (unattended) installation for Linux computers:

Url.Title: Installing a Collector on Linux with RPM
Url.Abstract: Installing a Collector on Linux with RPM The RPM installer uses a collector script to install a Collector to run as root on Linux 64 systems. By default, RPM installs the Collector in the /opt/SumoCollector directory.

Url.Title: Unattended installation for Windows
Url.Abstract: Unattended installation for Windows With all silent (unattended) installations, you'll first download the Collector, then configure a Source using a JSON file stored in the installation directory.

Url.Title: Silent Installation for Linux, Mac, Unix, and Windows using the Tarball
Url.Abstract: Silent Installation for Linux, Mac, Unix, and Windows using the Tarball Sumo Logic offers a generic tarball file that can be used to script unattended Collector installations for one or more Collectors. You'll need to download the tarball on each machine where you'll install a Collector and make sure that JSON has been configured for the Sources you'll use to collect data on each machine.

Url.Title: Using JSON to configure Sources
Url.Abstract: Using JSON to configure Sources The JSON files used to configure Sources follows the syntax used in the Collector Management API.

Url.Title: Using sumo.conf
Url.Abstract: Using sumo.conf The sumo.conf file allows you to pass Collector configuration parameters to Sumo Logic during installation. Once installation is complete, you may delete sumo.conf.

Url.Title: Using sumo.conf to disable Collector options
Url.Abstract: Using sumo.conf to disable Collector options In addition to configuring Sources, sumo.conf can be used to pass parameters to disable certain Collector options.

Url.Title: Forcing a Collector's Name with Clobber
Url.Abstract: Forcing a Collector's Name with Clobber During a scripted or manual installation, you can use the clobber flag in situations where you're creating a new Collector that will use a name that is already in use by another Collector. Clobber is only effective before the new Collector has been registered (activated) with Sumo Logic.

Url.Title: Setting a Collector as Ephemeral
Url.Abstract: Setting a Collector as Ephemeral Collector During the installation process, if a Collector is flagged as ephemeral, the Collector will be deleted automatically after being offline for 12 hours. This can be helpful when using certain APIs, for example, where Amazon Machine Images (AMIs) are constantly created as new Collectors, but serve a purpose for only a short while. After being offline for a while, the AMI-created Collector is automatically deleted.

Url.Title: Setting up Hosted Collectors and configuring Sources
Url.Abstract: Setting up Hosted Collectors and configuring Sources With Hosted Collectors and S3 Sources, data stored in your organization's S3 bucket can be uploaded into Sumo Logic, allowing you to perform the same searches and forensics on data no matter where it's stored. Additionally, HTTP Sources can be configured to upload data to Sumo Logic.

Url.Title: Setting up a Hosted Collector
Url.Abstract: Setting up a Hosted Collector A Hosted Collector is not installed on a local system in your deployment. Instead, Sumo Logic hosts the Collector (along with a Collector's Sources) in AWS. With a Hosted Collector, you can configure S3 Sources, allowing you to move data from your S3 bucket directly in to Sumo Logic, or HTTP Sources, that you'll use to upload data through a secure URL. A single Hosted Collector can be configured with any number of S3 and HTTP Sources.

Url.Title: Adding an Amazon S3 Source
Url.Abstract: Adding an Amazon S3 Source After setting up a Hosted Collector, you'll add an Amazon S3 Source. Before adding the Source, make sure that your AWS account is set up properly. Learn more in Granting access to an S3 bucket.

Url.Title: Configuring an Amazon S3 Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring an Amazon S3 Source After setting up a Hosted Collector, you'll need to configure an S3 Source to begin collecting data from an S3 bucket.

Url.Title: Granting Access to an S3 bucket
Url.Abstract: Granting Access to an S3 bucket Before configuring an S3 Source, you'll need to grant Sumo Logic permissions to get objects and object versions, and list object and object versions in your organization's bucket. First you'll need to make sure that your AWS account includes IAM. You can enable IAM through the AWS control panel.

Url.Title: About setting the S3 Scan Interval
Url.Abstract: About setting the S3 Scan Interval When configuring an S3 Source, you'll set the Scan Interval, which defines the waiting time between scans of the objects in your S3 bucket.

Url.Title: Configuring an HTTP Source
Url.Abstract: Configuring an HTTP Source An HTTP Source is an endpoint for receiving a file (or a batch of files) uploaded via a unique URL generated for the Source. The URL securely encodes the Collector and Source information. You can add as many HTTP Sources as you'd like to a single Hosted Collector.

Url.Title: Uploading data to an HTTP Source
Url.Abstract: Uploading data to an HTTP Source Once an HTTP Source has been added to a Hosted Collector you can begin uploading data. All files are uploaded over HTTPS, meaning that your data is secure.

Url.Title: Generating a new URL
Url.Abstract: Generating a new URL You can generate a new URL for an HTTP Source at any time. Note that generating a new URL completely invalidates the old URL.

Url.Title: Using the Sumo Logic Web Application
Url.Abstract: Using the Sumo Logic Web Application The Sumo Logic Web Application connects you to your raw source data in the cloud. With a powerful and intuitive search capability, you can use the web application to expedite functions like forensic analysis, troubleshooting, and system health checks.

Url.Title: Understanding the Web Application user interface
Url.Abstract: Understanding the Web Application user interface The Sumo Logic Web Application is made up of several pages that you can use to analyze your data, manage Collectors and Sources, view users in your organization, and otherwise keep an eye on your deployment.

Url.Title: Navigating through Messages in the Search Tab
Url.Abstract: Navigating through Messages in the Search Tab When you run a search query, messages display in the Message, Aggregates, or Summarize tabs in the lower half of the browser window. Results are paginated with 15 messages per page.

Url.Title: Using the Status page
Url.Abstract: Using the Status page The Status page provides a visual snapshot of the overall message history for your deployment, as well as a message volume histogram for each Collector, giving you immediate visual feedback about traffic spikes or collection issues.To see statistics for any bar in the histogram, hover your mouse pointer over the area of interest.

Url.Title: Account page
Url.Abstract: Account page The Account page displays the data limits of your organization's account to help you keep an eye on how much data you're uploading to Sumo Logic.

Url.Title: Preferences page
Url.Abstract: Preferences page The Preferences page displays options you can use to configure the Sumo Logic Web Application.

Url.Title: Changing your password
Url.Abstract: Changing your password You can change your password at any time through the Sumo Logic Web Application.

Url.Title: Web Application Keyboard Shortcuts
Url.Abstract: Web Application Keyboard Shortcuts Shortcuts in the Web App are triggered with a keystroke pattern of g and a second letter.

Url.Title: Searching and Analyzing
Url.Abstract: Searching and Analyzing Sumo Logic’s extensive query options help you fain valuable insight into your log messages. Sumo Logic collects and processes all your logs in real time so that you can search the most up-to-the-minute information:

Url.Title: Search
Url.Abstract: The basis of Sumo Logic Search is a funnel or "pipeline" concept, where keywords and operators are separated by pipes ("|"). First, the search finds the results from the keyword expression. Then, each operator acts on the results from the previous operator to further process your results. Results are returned incrementally with the most recent messages displaying first. Additional messages are added progressively to the Messages tab as the search walks backward in time through all of your log data.

Url.Title: Running a basic search
Url.Abstract: Running a basic search After configuring Sources to collect the events and logs you need, you can begin using search within minutes. Sumo Logic search syntax uses logical and familiar operators allowing you to create ad hoc queries quickly and efficiently. You can save searches to re-use later or to run as regularly scheduled searches that can be delivered to your email address.

Url.Title: Saving a Search
Url.Abstract: Saving a Search Whether you are running ad hoc searches during a forensic investigation or running standard searches for health checks, you can save any search query for reuse. When you save a search, you have the option to set up the saved search to run at a scheduled interval with an automated notification by email of the search results. You can edit a saved search at any time.

Url.Title: Sharing a Link to a Search
Url.Abstract: Sharing a Link to a Search A search query can be shared ad-hoc by sending another user in your organization a Search Code. Clicking the Share Search Code icon creates a link that you can copy and paste. Then, the recipient can paste the link in the Search text box and run the search. Please note that search results may vary depending on each user's permissions.

Url.Title: Setting the Time Range of a Search
Url.Abstract: Setting the Time Range of a Search You'll enter time parameters for your search to the right of the Search field:

Url.Title: Parsing and Naming a Field
Url.Abstract: Parsing and Naming a Field The parse operator parses strings according to specified start and stop anchors, and then labels them as fields for use in subsequent actions such as sorting, grouping, or even math expressions.

Url.Title: Pausing or Canceling a Search
Url.Abstract: Pausing or Canceling a Search When a search is in progress, the options to Cancel or Pause the search appear.

Url.Title: Modifying a Search from the Messages Tab
Url.Abstract: Modifying a Search from the Messages Tab After running a search, you can modify subsequent searches by selecting text displayed in the Messages tab. After selecting text, you can choose how to modify the search using the options from a pop-up menu:

Url.Title: How Metadata is used in searches
Url.Abstract: How Metadata is used in searches Sumo Logic attaches metadata tags to your log messages when the data is collected. Metadata tags are very useful when you're searching log data—they allow you to quickly identify the Collector or Source the data was ingested from, the type of logs, and so on. Some metadata fields are determined by the values you enter when installing a Collector or configuring a Source; these fields can be edited at any time.

Url.Title: Searching Surrounding Messages
Url.Abstract: Searching Surrounding Messages Surrounding messages allow you to investigate events surrounding a message from the context of the Host, file name or category identified enabling you to view the activity for the defined time period. As you browse results in the Messages list, you might come across a message where you would like to see more context: What other events occurred just before and after this event? What else was happening on this host at the same time? When you search surrounding messages, you capture the context of the current message to gain insight into surrounding activity.

Url.Title: Exporting Search Results
Url.Abstract: Exporting Search Results After running a search query, you can download the results from your browser as a CSV (comma-separated text) file.

Url.Title: Graphing Search Results
Url.Abstract: Graphing Search Results In addition to the standard table view, aggregated search results be viewed as a bar graph.

Url.Title: Setting Messages pane preferences
Url.Abstract: Setting Messages pane preferences Preferences in the Messages pane allow you to customize how messages are displayed. You'll find the menu in the Messages pane. Just click the preferences icon:

Url.Title: Parsing
Url.Abstract: Parsing Sumo Logic provides a number of ways to parse fields in your log messages: Parse operator. Automatically parses and names a field.

Url.Title: Parse Operator
Url.Abstract: Parse Operator The Parse (or Parse Anchor) operator parses strings according to specified start and stop anchors, and then labels them as fields for use in subsequent aggregation functions in the query such as sorting, grouping, or other functions. For help in learning to parse strings, see Extracting and Naming a Field.

Url.Title: Parse Regex or Extract Operator
Url.Abstract: Parse Regex or Extract Operator Parse regex (or "extract") enables users comfortable with regular expression syntax to extract more complex data from log lines. Parse regex can be used, for example, to extract nested fields.

Url.Title: Parsing multiple values in a field
Url.Abstract: Parsing multiple values in a field In addition to parsing a field, the multi option allows you to parse multiple values within a single field. This means that Multi keyword instructs the parse regex operator to not just look for the first value in a field but for all of the values, even in messages with a varying number of values in a field. As a part of this process, the multi keyword creates copies of each message so that each individual value in a field can be counted.

Url.Title: Parse nodrop Option
Url.Abstract: Parse nodrop Option For all parse operators, messages must match at least one segment of the parse expression or they are dropped from the results. Adding the "nodrop" option forces results to also include messages that do not match any segment of the parse term.

Url.Title: Using Parser Libary
Url.Abstract: To expedite searching and analysis for common log types, Sumo Logic offers Parser Libraries. Each Parser Library is a set of parsing definitions written to automatically extract field values from a specific type of raw data. Rather than writing field parsing rules yourself, you can apply a parser library to your search to automatically extract fields from the logs, and then use the resulting parsed fields to extend your query.

Url.Title: Parsing Apache Logs
Url.Abstract: Parsing Apache Logs This parser library processes the logs from Apache web servers in the NCSA extended/combined log format.

Url.Title: Parsing Apache Access Logs
Url.Abstract: Parsing Apache Access Logs The Apache access log parser extracts and labels the following fields. Field Name

Url.Title: Parsing Apache Error Logs
Url.Abstract: Parsing Apache Error Logs The Apache error log parser extracts and labels the following fields. Field Name

Url.Title: Parsing Cisco ASA Logs
Url.Abstract: Parsing Cisco ASA Logs The Cisco ASA parser assumes that interfaces, IP addresses, and port tuples are either "Source" or "Destination" tuples, and categorizes each according to the flow specified in the message. The Source interface is assumed to be the default; the Source Host is assumed to be the default host.

Url.Title: Parsing Microsoft IIS Logs
Url.Abstract: Parsing Microsoft IIS Logs The Microsoft IIS parser extracts and labels the following fields. The Microsoft IIS parser assumes that logs are coming in the default IIS W3C format for IIS 7.0.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic Suggested Searches
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic Suggested Searches To better understand how Sumo Logic queries can help track and diagnose common IT issues like monitoring traffic from devices, failed network logins, kernel failures, or many other issues, take a look at these Sumo Logic Suggested Searches:

Url.Title: Searches for the Apache Access Parser
Url.Abstract: Searches for the Apache Access Parser The following searches were built for use with the Apache Access Parser. Copy and paste these searches into the search query field and save them for use later.

Url.Title: Searches for the Apache Errors Parser
Url.Abstract: Searches for the Apache Errors Parser The following searches were built for use with the Apache Errors Parser. Copy and paste these searches into the search query field and save them for use later. You can also set up threshold alerts for the Critical Operations Errors to be notified in the event critical errors occur.

Url.Title: Searches for the Cisco ASA Parser
Url.Abstract: Searches for the Cisco ASA Parser These suggested searches cover some of the most common scenarios for monitoring Security, Audit, and Performance issues on a Linux server. You can enter these queries into the Search field of the Sumo Logic Web Application as a starting baseline, and then customize the queries for your system. Be sure to save your search queries if you plan to run them often.

Url.Title: Suggested Searches for Linux OS Systems
Url.Abstract: Suggested Searches for Linux OS Systems These suggested searches cover some of the most common scenarios for monitoring user activity and security activity on a Linux server. These searches should work on RedHat, Debian, SuSe platforms, as well as their derivations (e.g. CentOS, Ubuntu, OpenSuSe).

Url.Title: Searches for the Microsoft IIS Parser
Url.Abstract: Searches for the Microsoft IIS Parser The following searches were built for use with the Microsoft IIS Parser. Copy and paste these searches into the search query field and save them for use later.

Url.Title: Using the Content Library
Url.Abstract: Using the Content Library The Content Library provides a central location for shared and saved content in your Sumo Logic account, as well as content shared by others in your organization. In addition to shared and saved searches, Dashboards can be saved and shared in the Content Library.

Url.Title: How the Content Library works
Url.Abstract: How the Content Library works The Content Library provides a single interface to organize and share searches and Dashboards. Folders make it easy to organize your content. By default, each user in an account has two folders: Saved and Shared. Content stored in the Saved folder is private until a user publishes a search or Dashboard. Content in the Shared folder is shared with all users across an organization’s account.

Url.Title: Scheduling searches
Url.Abstract: Scheduling searches There are two ways of setting up scheduled searches. You can elect to receive a summary email, where the subject of the email is titled Search Results. This type of email contains a summary of the search results for your information or use. The email will arrive as scheduled, depending on the frequency the search is run.These emails, with the subject of Search Alert, will only arise when the conditions you set are met. For example, you could set up an alert if a certain number of users visit the free trial URL of your website. You can run a search from this email as well.

Url.Title: Canceling or Editing Scheduled Searches
Url.Abstract: Canceling or Editing Scheduled Searches You can edit or cancel a scheduled search at any time. If you cancel a scheduled search, the search reverts to a saved search.

Url.Title: Running a Search from an Alert Email
Url.Abstract: Running a Search from an Alert Email When you receive an alert email from a scheduled search, only a representative sample of the results are included. (We don't want to backup anyone's email with hundreds of thousands of search results.)

Url.Title: Setting up Real Time Alerts
Url.Abstract: Setting up Real Time Alerts This feature is only available to customers with Enterprise accounts, or those in paid trials. If you'd like to try using Real Time Alerts, please contact your sales representative.

Url.Title: Adding content
Url.Abstract: Adding content With the Content Library you can save, edit, delete, and publish (share) searches and Dashboards. Of course you can launch a search and open a Dashboard with a single click.

Url.Title: Publishing Content from the Content Library
Url.Abstract: Publishing Content from the Content Library Once you’ve saved content, you can choose to publish it, making it available for subscription. Published content is automatically added to your Shared folder.

Url.Title: Publishing Dashboards
Url.Abstract: Publishing Dashboards Publishing a Dashboard is a great way to keep everyone on top of data that is important to your organization. After a Dashboard is published others can subscribe to it, which means that any changes you make will also be reflected in the subscribers' accounts.

Url.Title: Subscribing to Content
Url.Abstract: Subscribing to Content You can subscribe to content stored in other user’s Shared folder. Once you subscribe, you’ll choose a folder to store the search or Dashboard; any changes the owner makes will be reflected in the copy stored in your library.

Url.Title: About Dashboards
Url.Abstract: About Dashboards Dashboards contain a collection of real-time Monitors that provide a graphical representation of your organization's data. The information you save in a Dashboard provides insight into the current state of the data you're uploading to Sumo Logic. Instead of having to run a number of queries, Sumo Logic runs these searches automatically, making sure that you're never looking at stale data. You won't have to remember to run important searches once you save them to Dashboards--you'll be able to spend your time gaining insight into what's happening in your organization.

Url.Title: Using Dashboards in Sumo Logic Free Accounts
Url.Abstract: Using Dashboards in Sumo Logic Free Accounts Dashboards in Sumo Logic Free accounts work the same was as those in Enterprise accounts with one limitation: organizations with Sumo Logic Free accounts have access to 20 Monitors, shared between the three users in the account. You can decide to build as many Dashboards as you'd like with the available Monitors in your account.

Url.Title: Adding Monitors to a Dashboard
Url.Abstract: Adding Monitors to a Dashboard Almost any query you run that produces aggregate results can be saved as a Monitor in a Dashboard. Aggregating (grouping) functions evaluate messages and place them into groups. After a search completes, you can choose a layout for the Monitor (although you'll be able to change the layout of the Monitor at any time), then either add the Monitor to an existing Dashboard or create a new Dashboard from the Monitor.

Url.Title: Launching a search from a Monitor
Url.Abstract: Launching a search from a Monitor Whether your working with a Dashboard you designed or from a shared Dashboard, you can click a data point in a Monitor to launch a search from that point in time. This is especially useful in situations where you've noticed activity in a Monitor that you'd like to research further.

Url.Title: Zooming in on a Monitor
Url.Abstract: Zooming in on a Monitor The Zoom icon allows you to view a single Monitor. The zoomed Monitor fills the browser window, so you control the size of the Monitor.

Url.Title: Editing Dashboards and Monitors
Url.Abstract: Editing Dashboards and Monitors Several Monitor properties can be edited directly from a Dashboard. (If you'd like to edit the query saved as a Monitor,see Saving changes back to a Monitor.) When editing a Dashboard or Monitor, you'll use the Properties menu:

Url.Title: Changing Monitor chart properties
Url.Abstract: Changing Monitor chart properties The colors used in a Monitor are assigned randomly. You can change the color at any time by editing the Chart properties. You'll also find the option to change the way labels are truncated.

Url.Title: Changing the axis of a Monitor
Url.Abstract: Changing the axis of a Monitor You can change the minimum and maximum values of a Monitor if you'd like to influence the results in a Monitor. You can also set the Monitor to use Log Scale, if you'd like.

Url.Title: Changing the name of a Dashboard or Monitor
Url.Abstract: Changing the name of a Dashboard or Monitor The names of Dashboard and Monitors can be changed at any time.

Url.Title: Changing the time range of a Monitor
Url.Abstract: Changing the time range of a Monitor Once you've created a Monitor you can change the time range at any time.

Url.Title: Changing the color of a bar or column by value range
Url.Abstract: Changing the color of a bar or column by value range When viewing search results displayed as a bar chart or column chart in Dashboard Monitors or in the Search tab, you can choose to change the color of a bar or column depending on the value range of the search output. This setting doesn't affect the query; it's only applied to query results.

Url.Title: Changing the type of a Monitor
Url.Abstract: Changing the type of a Monitor If you'd like to change the way a Monitor is displayed in a Dashboard you can choose a different layout.

Url.Title: Saving edits to a Monitor
Url.Abstract: Saving edits to a Monitor After running a search from a Monitor, any edits made to the query can be saved back to the Monitor; these changes are immediately reflected in the Monitor. In addition to fine-tuning the query, the time range of the Monitor can also be changed.

Url.Title: Creating combo chart Monitors
Url.Abstract: Creating combo chart Monitors Combo charts allow you to create bar or column chart with a secondary vertical axis so you can add a separate line as a comparison. For example, say we're running query like:

Url.Title: Creating Box Plot Charts
Url.Abstract: Creating Box Plot Charts A Box Plot Chart graphically depicts groups of data using their quartiles. In Box Plot charts, the bottom and top of the box represent the first and third quartiles; the band inside the box represents the median:

Url.Title: Setting Firefox Permissions to View Dashboards
Url.Abstract: Setting Firefox Permissions to View Dashboards When using Firefox to view Dashboards, you'll need to enable an option that allows Sumo Logic to change the order of open browser windows. In Firefox, it's referred to as raising and lowering (bringing to front or moving to back) windows.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic Operators and Expressions
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic Operators and Expressions This section provides detailed syntax, rules, and examples for Sumo Logic Operators, Expressions, and Search Language.

Url.Title: Search Syntax Overview
Url.Abstract: Search Syntax Overview The Sumo Logic Search Language operates on your entire log repository, no matter how many different log sources you have—in real time. The search query language is intuitive and efficient, allowing you to search terabytes of data and see results in seconds.

Url.Title: Keyword Search Expression
Url.Abstract: Keyword Search Expression For simplicity, we refer to the search expression before the first pipe as a "keyword" expression. In fact, this portion of the query is a powerful, full-text search engine. Boolean logic and wildcards enable you to search for multiple terms, express logic about term distribution within messages, and specify partial terms with wildcards. The keyword expression also encompasses metadata searches for fields such as _collector, _sourceCategory, _sourceName, and _sourceHost.

Url.Title: Wildcards in Full Text Searches
Url.Abstract: Wildcards in Full Text Searches For the most part, the asterisk (*) wildcard works the way you would expect in the keyword (full-text search) expression ("*" represents zero or more characters). This topic covers the details and special cases when using wildcards, for example, within quoted search expressions and within phrase queries.

Url.Title: Conditional Expressions
Url.Abstract: Conditional Expressions Conditional expressions filter results by evaluating against a criterion. Only results that meet the criterion are returned.

Url.Title: Where Operator
Url.Abstract: Where Operator To filter results in a search query, use "where" as a conditional operator. The where operator must appear as a separate operator distinct from other operators, delimited by the pipe symbol ("|"). In other words, the following construct will not work and will generate a syntax error:

Url.Title: Ternary Expressions: Using 'If' or '?'
Url.Abstract: Ternary Expressions: Using 'If' or '?' ?' There are two forms of ternary expression you can use in Sumo Logic queries: one is constructed with the question mark (?) operator, and the other is constructed using the IF operator. The syntax varies slightly, but the results are equivalent. You can use the syntax you're most comfortable with.

Url.Title: Accum operator
Url.Abstract: Accum operator The accum operator calculates the cumulative sum of a field. The accum operator can be used to find a count by a specific time interval, and can be used to find a total running count across all intervals.

Url.Title: CIDR Operator
Url.Abstract: CIDR Operator The CIDR operator allows you to leverage Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) notations to analyze IP network traffic in order to narrow analysis to specific subnets. CIDR notations specify the routing prefix of IP addresses (learn more here). Using the CIDR operator, you can determine the amount of traffic between network segments, review events from hosts within a specified network segment, or even use a not operator to find addresses that didn't originate from a particular network segment.

Url.Title: Difference (Diff) Operator
Url.Abstract: Difference (Diff) Operator The diff operator calculates the rate of change in a field between consecutive rows. To produce results, diff requires that a specified field contain numeric data; any non-numerical values are removed from the search results.

Url.Title: Fields Operator
Url.Abstract: Fields Operator The fields operator allows you to choose which fields are displayed in the results of a query. Use a fields operator to reduce the "clutter" of a search output that contains fields that aren't completely relevant to your query.

Url.Title: Mapping IP addresses with the geo lookup operator
Url.Abstract: Mapping IP addresses with the geo lookup operator Sumo Logic can now match an extracted IP address to it's geographical location on a map. To create the map, after parsing the IP addresses from log files, the lookup operator matches extracted IP addresses to the physical location where the addresses originated. Finally, geo-location fields are used by the Google Maps API to add the IPs to a map. The latitude and longitude fields are required; optional fields are country_code, country_name, region, city, postal_code, area_code, and metro_code. Depending on how specific you’d like the output to be, you can include all the optional fields, or choose a subset.

Url.Title: Group Operator and Group-By Functions
Url.Abstract: Group Operator and Group-By Functions Aggregating functions evaluate messages and place them into groups. The group operator is used in conjunction with group-by functions. When using any grouping function, the word by is sufficient for representing the group operator. The typical construction when using group-by functions is:

Url.Title: avg
Url.Abstract: avg The averaging function (avg) calculates average value of the numerical field being evaluated within the time range analyzed.

Url.Title: count, count_distinct, and count_frequent
Url.Abstract: count, count_distinct, and count_frequent Aggregating (group-by) functions are used in conjunction with the group operator and a field name. Only the word by is required to represent the group operator. The count function is also an operator in its own right and therefore can be used with or without the word by.

Url.Title: first and last
Url.Abstract: first and last In general terms, first finds the earliest occurrence in search results, and last finds the result that follows all others, based on the sort order for the query

Url.Title: min and max
Url.Abstract: min and max Use the min and max functions to find the smallest or largest value in a set of values. max

Url.Title: pct
Url.Abstract: pct The percentile function (pct) finds the percentile of a given field. Multiple pct functions can be included in one query.

Url.Title: stddev
Url.Abstract: stddev The standard deviation function (stddev) finds the standard deviation value for a distribution of numerical values within the time range analyzed and associated with a group designated by the "group by" field.

Url.Title: sum
Url.Abstract: sum Sum adds the values of the numerical field being evaluated within the time range analyzed. Syntax: sum(numerical_field)

Url.Title: isNull Operator
Url.Abstract: isNull Operator The isNull operator takes a single parameter and returns a boolean value: True if the variable is indeed null, or false if the variable contains a value other than null.

Url.Title: Join operator
Url.Abstract: Join operator The Join operator combines records two or more data streams. Results are admitted on-the-fly to allow real-time tables to be built. Values common to each table are then delivered as search results.

Url.Title: JSON Operator
Url.Abstract: JSON Operator The JSON Operator is a search query language operator that allows you to extract values from JSON input. Because JSON supports both nested keys and arrays that contain ordered sequences of values, the Sumo Logic JSON Operator allows you to extract:

Url.Title: Keyvalue operator
Url.Abstract: Keyvalue operator Typically, log files contain information that follow a key-value structure. The keyvalue operator allows you to get values from a log message by specifying the key associated with each value.

Url.Title: Limit Operator
Url.Abstract: Limit Operator The limit operator reduces the number of raw messages or aggregate results returned. If you simply query for a particular term, for example "error" without using an aggregation operator such as group by, limit will reduce the number of raw messages returned. If you first use group-by or other aggregation operator, the limit operator will reduce the number of grouped results instead.

Url.Title: Matches Operator
Url.Abstract: Matches Operator The matches operator can be used to match a string to a pattern. The return of the operator is boolean; the operator can be used with where or if expressions.

Url.Title: Math Expressions
Url.Abstract: Math Expressions You can use general mathematical expressions on numerical data extracted from log lines. For any mathematical or group-by function that implicitly requires integers, Sumo Logic casts the string data to a number for you.

Url.Title: Using the Sessionize Operator
Url.Abstract: Using the Sessionize Operator The Sessionize operator allows you to use an extracted value from one log message (generated from one system) to find correlating values in log messages from other systems. After you run Sessionize these related events are displayed on the same page. The thread of logs woven together is called a session.

Url.Title: Smooth Operator
Url.Abstract: Smooth Operator The smooth operator calculates the rolling (or moving) average of a field, measuring the average of a value to "smooth" random variation. Smooth operator reveals trends in the data set you include in a query.

Url.Title: Sort or Top Operators
Url.Abstract: Sort or Top Operators The sort operator orders aggregated search results. Use top to reduce the number of sorted results returned. The default sort order is descending.

Url.Title: Summarize Operator
Url.Abstract: Summarize Operator The Summarize Operator's algorithm uses fuzzy logic to cluster messages together based on string and pattern similarity. You can use the summarize operator to quickly assess activity patterns for things like a range of devices or traffic on a website. Focus the summarize algorithm on an area of interest by defining that area in the keyword expression. For information on how to interpret and influence the outcome of Summarize results, see Detecting Patterns with Summarize. To learn how to refine Summarize results, see Influencing the Summarize Outcome.htm.

Url.Title: Detecting patterns with summarize
Url.Abstract: Detecting patterns with summarize The Summarize algorithm uses fuzzy logic and soft matching to group messages with similar structures and common repeated text strings into signatures, providing a quick investigative view, or snapshot, for the keywords or time range provided.

Url.Title: Viewing Summarize Details
Url.Abstract: Viewing Summarize Details From the Summarize tab, you can view logs grouped together in a signature to view the raw log data by clicking the number in the Count column:

Url.Title: Influencing the Summarize Outcome
Url.Abstract: Influencing the Summarize Outcome The Summarize algorithm uses fuzzy logic and soft matching to group messages with similar structures and common repeated text strings into signatures, providing a quick investigative view, or snapshot, for the keywords or time range provided. Summarized data is based on the data available to the algorithm during the time range of your search. In some cases, this sampling of data produces results that don't meet your needs. You can influence the algorithm by editing a signature to make the results more general, or see more granular results by splitting a signature. In addition you can promote or demote a signature to help Sumo Logic understand what data is the most relevant to you.

Url.Title: Editing a Summarize Signature
Url.Abstract: Editing a Summarize Signature Editing a signature allows you to choose values that should be treated as wildcards. After you replace one or more values with a wildcard (*****) the summarize algorithm treats each value as the same, which expands the number of results.

Url.Title: Understanding the Summarize Relevance column
Url.Abstract: Understanding the Summarize Relevance column The Summarize Relevance column displays a numerical score for a signature, predicting which signatures could be most meaningful to a user. The Relevance value is computed using your history of feedback (Thumbs Up and Thumbs Down) and the instances when you’ve chosen to view the details of signatures.

Url.Title: Using Summarize Delta
Url.Abstract: Using Summarize Delta With Summarize Delta, you can save a baseline summarize pattern, and then later run a delta against the baseline. Sumo Logic will report the variance giving you insight into the shifts in patterns over time.

Url.Title: Using summarize on JSON logs
Url.Abstract: Using summarize on JSON logs If you're collecting JSON logs, summarize can be used to analyze a single field instead of full raw messages. This avoids having summarize consider the repetitive headers and metadata in JSON logs. Make sure to choose a field that contains enough data for summarize to detect patterns; fields that output short value strings may not produce meaningful results.

Url.Title: Time Expressions
Url.Abstract: Time Expressions When you are building a search query, you have the option to add a time expression in a separate field. Preset values are available to choose from, with Last 15 Minutes as the default start value and "now" being the implied end time. In cases where more control of the start and end time is required, a time range expression can be typed directly into the time range field.

Url.Title: Timeslice Operator
Url.Abstract: Timeslice Operator The timeslice operator segregates data by time period, so you can create bucketed results based on a fixed width in time, for example, five minute periods. Timeslice also supports bucketing by a fixed number of buckets across the search results, for example, 150 buckets over the last 60 minutes. An alias for the timeslice field is optional. When an alias is not provided, a default _timeslice field is created.

Url.Title: Total operator
Url.Abstract: Total operator The total operator calculates the grand total of a field and injects that value into every row.

Url.Title: Trace Operator
Url.Abstract: Trace Operator A trace operator acts as a highly sophisticated filter to connect the dots across different log messages. You can use any identifying value with a trace operator (such as a user ID, IP address, session ID, etc.) to retrieve a comprehensive set of activity associated to that original ID.

Url.Title: Transpose Operator
Url.Abstract: Transpose Operator The transpose operator dynamically creates columns for aggregate search results. The dynamic functionality allows for changing the output of a query, turning search results into fields. It also means that queries can be designed without first knowing the output schema.

Url.Title: URL Decode Operator
Url.Abstract: URL Decode Operator The URL Decode (urldecode) operator decodes a URL you include in a query, returning the decoded (unescaped) URL string.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic Administration
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic Administration Admins of Sumo Logic accounts have access to several Administration tools used to manage a deployment, including:

Url.Title: Managing Collectors and Sources
Url.Abstract: Managing Collectors and Sources In the Collectors tab of the Sumo Logic Web Application, you will see a list of all the Collectors and Sources in your current Sumo Logic deployment. You can manage your Collectors and Sources from this page.

Url.Title: Editing a Collector
Url.Abstract: Editing a Collector From the Collectors tab of the Sumo Logic Web Application, you can edit some characteristics of a Collector, including its name, description, Host Name, and Category.

Url.Title: Starting or stopping a Sumo Logic Collector
Url.Abstract: Starting or stopping a Sumo Logic Collector Sumo Logic Collectors start automatically at system startup. Manually restarting or stopping a Sumo Logic Collector requires root (Mac and Linux) or Administrator (Windows) privileges.

Url.Title: Filtering Source Data
Url.Abstract: Filtering Source Data Regular expressions are used to create rules that filter data sent to Sumo Logic from a Source. The filters affect only the data sent to Sumo Logic; logs on your end remain intact and unchanged. There are four different types of filters you can apply:

Url.Title: Include and Exclude filters
Url.Abstract: Include and Exclude filters You can use include and exclude filters to specify what kind of data is sent to the Sumo Logic Cloud. If you specifically exclude a message, it will never be sent to Sumo Logic. Think of an exclude filter as a blacklist filter.

Url.Title: Hash filters
Url.Abstract: Hash filters With a hash filter, whatever expression you choose to hash will be replaced by a hash code generated for that value. Hashed data is completely hidden (obfuscated) before being sent to Sumo Logic. This can be very useful in situations where some type of data must not leave your premises (such as credit card numbers, social security, numbers, etc.). Each unique value will have a unique hash code.

Url.Title: Mask filters
Url.Abstract: Mask filters When you create a mask filter, whatever expression you choose to mask will be replaced with a mask string before it's sent to Sumo Logic (you can either select the character or use the default, #). For example, to mask all users' email addresses, you could use the following:

Url.Title: Creating filters
Url.Abstract: Creating filters To create a filter for a Source: Do one of the following: To create a filter for an existing Source, in the Collectors page click Edit next to a Source. Click the drop-down selector next to Filter, and then click Add Filter.

Url.Title: Establishing Metadata Conventions
Url.Abstract: Establishing Metadata Conventions Prior to installing Collectors, it is a good idea to establish predefined naming conventions for Sources, Collectors, and especially metadata tags. Sumo Logic Search supports the use of metadata tags in your messages such as Source Host and Source Category. This metadata is attached to your log messages at collection-time. All metadata is determined by the values you enter when configuring a Source. These tags are very important since they provide valuable keywords and terms you can use to find targeted results in search queries.

Url.Title: Managing Ingestion
Url.Abstract: Managing Ingestion The rate of data creation is rarely constant. Whether your organization sees seasonal spikes, or if a new feature or product line produces huge increases in activity, Sumo Logic meets the needs of your organization, known or unknown, while maintaining the search performance you rely on.

Url.Title: Using Role-Based Access Control with Sumo Logic
Url.Abstract: Using Role-Based Access Control with Sumo Logic Sumo Logic now supports Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) to allow Administrators to customize system access. With RBAC, Administrators create roles that are created for groups of users who perform various job functions. Users are not assigned permissions directly, but inherit permissions through roles (or even through a single role). Role assignments can grant users permissions to access some data sets, or can restrict users from accessing types of data.

Url.Title: Managing User Roles
Url.Abstract: Managing User Roles Administrators of Sumo Logic accounts are able to create, edit, and delete roles to maintain compliance with internal data access policies.

Url.Title: Understanding default user roles
Url.Abstract: Understanding default user roles There are two default roles assigned to users in a Sumo Logic account: Administrator and Analyst. These roles are assigned to any users already in your organization's Sumo Logic account.

Url.Title: Defining custom roles
Url.Abstract: Defining custom roles Roles are specified using search language constructs in a Query String. The string is added silently to every query run by a user assigned to a role.

Url.Title: Creating a new role
Url.Abstract: Creating a new role New roles are created in the Manage Roles page of the Users tab. Click Manage > Users in the Sumo Logic Web Application.

Url.Title: Constructing a query string
Url.Abstract: Constructing a query string A Query String defines access for a role. Limitations can be set based on several types of metadata, or at the record level. String are silently added to the beginning of each query a user runs.

Url.Title: Assigning roles to users
Url.Abstract: Assigning roles to users Before you implement RBAC, all of the users in your account are assigned either the Administrator or Analyst default role (depending on which role they had previously).

Url.Title: Editing or deleting roles
Url.Abstract: Editing or deleting roles Roles can be edited at any time. Query strings can be modified, and Collector Permissions can be changed. You can also change the users assigned to a role.

Url.Title: Managing Users
Url.Abstract: Managing Users Creating new users, as well as editing the roles and credentials of existing users, is managed through the Sumo Logic Web Application.

Url.Title: Creating a new user
Url.Abstract: Creating a new user When you create a new user, you'll need to make sure to assign at least one role to the user; no default roles are given to a new user.

Url.Title: Editing user credentials or roles
Url.Abstract: Editing user credentials or roles When you add or remove a role from a user the change is implemented right away, granting the user the highest level of access of the combined roles.

Url.Title: Deactivating a user
Url.Abstract: Deactivating a user To temporarily prevent a user from logging into the Sumo Logic service, you can change the user's status to Inactive. You can reactivate an inactive user at any time without the need to re-enter user details. If you wish to permanently remove a user, you can delete them.

Url.Title: Deleting a user
Url.Abstract: Deleting a user Deleting a user permanently removes the user and his or her associated settings, including scheduled and shared searches and shared Dashboards. To save the settings for a user and temporarily prevent access, you can deactivate a user rather than deleting them.

Url.Title: Resetting a user's password
Url.Abstract: Resetting a user's password The following procedure is for Admins to use to reset another user's password.

Url.Title: Data Forwarding
Url.Abstract: Data Forwarding This feature is only available to customers with Enterprise accounts, or those in paid trials. If you'd like to try Data Forwarding, please contact your sales representative.

Url.Title: Managing Security Settings
Url.Abstract: Managing Security Settings The Security page of the Sumo Logic Web Application makes it easy to manage security policies in one place:

Url.Title: Setting password policies
Url.Abstract: Setting password policies Account Admins can set the account's password policy through the Security page. There are several components that can be customized:

Url.Title: Whitelisting IP or CIDR addresses
Url.Abstract: Whitelisting IP or CIDR addresses Service Whitelist Settings allow you to explicitly grant access to specific IP addresses and/or CIDR notations. By default this feature is not enabled. The IP address of the Admin who enables the feature is automatically added to the whitelist. Once the feature is enabled, the IP address or CIDR of each user in an account must be added to the whitelist in order to log in to Sumo Logic.

Url.Title: Using Access Keys
Url.Abstract: Using Access Keys Access Keys are generated by an individual user in the Sumo Logic Web Applications; however, admins in the account can deactivate or delete all keys generated across the account. Access Keys are associated with the user who generated them; if a user is disabled, keys associated with that user will no longer work. When a user is removed from the account their keys will no longer authenticate.

Url.Title: Sumo Logic Beta Features
Url.Abstract: Sumo Logic Beta Features Want a sneak peek at the latest and greatest Sumo Logic features? You're in the right place!

Url.Title: Provisioning SAML
Url.Abstract: Provisioning SAML Sumo Logic now supports self-provisioning of Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) to enable Single Sign-On (SSO). In addition to basic SAML configuration, you can choose optional on-demand user creation (via SAML 2.0 assertions), and designate custom log in and/or log out portals.

Url.Title: Optional SAML features
Url.Abstract: Optional SAML features When configuring SAML, there are two optional features that you can use to set up how new user accounts are added, and where users are directed after logging out of Sumo Logic.

Url.Title: Viewing SAML debug information
Url.Abstract: Viewing SAML debug information When the Debug Mode option is selected, whenever an error occurs a debug page is displayed. The debug page is displayed in a new browser window (not within the Sumo Logic Web Application). A new page is generated for each error.

Url.Title: Lookup Operator
Url.Abstract: Lookup Operator Using a lookup operator, you can map data in your log messages to meaningful information. For example, you could use a lookup operator to map "userID" to a real user's name. Or, you could use a lookup operator to find black-listed IP addresses. In either case, you'll point the operator to one of the following:

Url.Title: Save Operator
Url.Abstract: Save Operator Using a Save operator allows you to save the results of a query into the Sumo Logic file system. Later, you can use the lookup operator to access the saved data. Save operator saves data in a simple format to a location you choose.

Url.Title: Adding a New Source
Url.Abstract: Adding a New Source During the setup process, you probably created your first Source. You can add more Sources to your Collectors at any time. Each Source is tagged with its own metadata (Source Host, Source Category and Source Name). The more Sources you set up, the easier it is to isolate one of the Sources in a Search since each Source can be identified by its metadata tags.

Url.Title: Adding a User or Editing User Details
Url.Abstract: Adding a User or Editing User Details From the Users tab of the Sumo Logic Web Application, you can add new users or edit the detailed settings for an existing user.

Url.Title: Manually Casting String Data to a Number
Url.Abstract: Manually Casting String Data to a Number Most data in Sumo Logic is stored as string type data. Metadata fields are stored as string data. And parsed fields are, by default, parsed as string type data. Sumo Logic will implicitly cast string data to a number type assuming it is clear that you need a number to perform an action, such as a math calculation or when using a function like sum or avg, However, if there is any ambiguity about whether a number is required, the data remains string data.

Url.Title: Group-By Functions
Url.Abstract: Group-By Functions Aggregating (group-by) functions are used in conjunction with the group operator and a field name. Aggregating functions always create a field named with a combination of an underscore (_) and the function name, such as _count, _count_distinct, _sum, _max, _stddev.

Url.Title: Managing Searches
Url.Abstract: Managing Searches Beyond ad hoc searches, you can save and share search queries in the Sumo Logic Web Application. To make it easier to manage all of your saved and shared search queries, they are saved in the search library. In addition, you can create scheduled searches that alert you to situations that could require immediate attention.

Url.Title: Parse Expressions
Url.Abstract: Parse Expressions Variations of the Parse operator are used to extract specific information from log messages. These include:

Url.Title: Using a Parser Library
Url.Abstract: Using a Parser Library Parser Libraries all you to apply a preconfigured library of parsing rules to evaluate messages according to pattern matches written as regular expressions.

Url.Title: Resetting a User's Password
Url.Abstract: Resetting a User's Password Users can reset their own passwords, or passwords can be reset by Administrators at any time.

Url.Title: Saving Dashboards
Url.Abstract: Saving Dashboards Content TBD.

Url.Title: Scheduling searches
Url.Abstract: Scheduling searches There are two ways of setting up scheduled searches. You can elect to receive a summary email, where the subject of the email is titled Search Results. This type of email contains a summary of the search results for your information or use. The email will arrive as scheduled, depending on the frequency the search is run. Scheduled searches can be edited or canceled at any time.

Url.Title: Sharing a Search in the Search Library
Url.Abstract: Sharing a Search in the Search Library Any saved search can be shared with the other users in your organization. When you share a search, the search appears by name in the Shared Searches library for all the Sumo Logic users in your organization. Anyone can run the search, but only you as the owner can edit the shared search query.

Url.Title: Fields, Limit, Sort, and Timeslice Operators
Url.Abstract: Fields, Limit, Sort, and Timeslice Operators The sort operator orders grouped results. The limit operator reduces the number of messages or grouped results returned. The timeslice operator groups messages by time range increments or by any number of "buckets" over a time range.

Url.Title: Choosing TCP or UDP
Url.Abstract: Choosing TCP or UDP When you configure a Syslog Source, you will need to choose a transfer protocol, either TCP or UDP. If your syslog-enabled devices have already been configured using TCP or UDP, choose the same protocol. If you are just setting up your devices, your first choice should probably be TCP.

Url.Title: Understanding Sumo Logic Sources
Url.Abstract: Understanding Sumo Logic Sources A Source is a logical partition for the data that a Collector gathers and sends to the Sumo Logic Cloud. You can set up as many Sources as you need for a given Collector. A Source should be configured to collect similar data types. For example, you might set up one Remote File Source to collect printer and router activity logs, and another Remote Source to collect status messages from appliances.

Url.Title: Managing Users and Roles
Url.Abstract: Managing Users and Roles In the Users tab of the Sumo Logic Web Application, you can view a list of users with access to your company data in the Sumo Logic Cloud. You can also provision new users, and delete or modify existing users.

Url.Title: Running queries from search libraries
Url.Abstract: Running queries from search libraries To make it easier to access all of your search queries, you can choose a search from a search library. Search libraries include:

Url.Title: Using Wildcards in Paths
Url.Abstract: Using Wildcards in Paths Rather than entering each file by name, using wildcards in the Source path allows you to collect all files of a certain type within one or more directories, or many files from many directories. When specifying file names (or paths) in Microsoft Windows and Unix-like operating systems, the asterisk character (*) substitutes for any zero or more characters, and the question mark (?) substitutes for any one character.
